{
  "doc_id": "3368",
  "text": "Several studies have identified groups of COPD subjects with metabolic and cardiovascular comorbidities. GarciaAymerich et al. identified a cluster of COPD patients with \"systemic COPD\" [CITATION_1] . These subjects were characterized by a high body mass index and very high rates of diabetes, congestive heart failure and ischemic heart disease; interestingly, they had higher levels of dyspnea and poorer health status than subjects with comparable airflow limitation, but less cardiovascular and metabolic comorbidities [CITATION_2] . Importantly, these patients were at high risk of hospitalization for cardiovascular events and also had substantial risk of hospitalization for COPD (despite having moderate airflow limitation) and all-cause mortality [CITATION_3] . These findings were consistent with those of Burgel et al. who reported marked differences between two clusters of subjects with comparable moderate to severe airflow limitation [CITATION_4] . Subjects with high rates of obesity, diabetes, and cardiovascular comorbidities had more symptoms and higher rates of exacerbations. Interestingly, these subjects were markedly older, a finding consistent with the increasing prevalence of cardiovascular diseases and obesity with age [CITATION_5] . Vanfleteren et al. also found a group of subjects with cardiovascular comorbidities but mostly normal BMI and suggested that this group differed from another one called \"metabolic\" in whom subjects showed high rates of obesity, dyslipidemia atherosclerosis, and myocardial infarction [CITATION_6] . Although it remains unclear whether COPD patients with cardiovascular versus metabolic comorbidities truly represent two different groups of patients, it is concluded that most studies identified these comorbidities in subsets of patients with worse prognosis compared to other COPD subjects. Burgel et al. have identified subjects with severe airflow limitation occurring at an early age in two different cohorts of COPD patients [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . These subjects were characterized by nutritional depletion [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] , high rates of emphysema and COPD exacerbations [CITATION_11] , muscle weakness, and high rates of osteoporosis [CITATION_12] , but very low rates of cardiovascular comorbidities [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] . In both studies, these subjects were at very high risk of mortality at a relatively young age [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] , suggesting that specific therapeutic intervention should be targeted to this group of very severe patients. Interestingly, Vanfleteren et al. also found a cluster of cachectic subjects who were very similar to these latter subjects [CITATION_17] . These authors suggested that common pathophysiologic pathways may be responsible for the cooccurrence of emphysema, muscle wasting, and osteoporosis. Of note, women appeared most prevalent in the cachectic phenotype in all 3 studies [CITATION_18] [CITATION_19] [CITATION_20] , a finding that is consistent with data obtained in the Boston Early-Onset COPD study [CITATION_21] .",
